         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ When travelling on Yorks Peninsula ¶ Yorke Peninsula, SA. ¶  ¶ 6 years ago I found this plant growing in scrub lands near Point Turton. (at the bottom of the Peninsula) The peculiarity of its appea...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">91.03.30a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Walter Gill</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M67, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style=""/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Found with specimen of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Apalochlamys spectabilis</seg>
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(MEL 717976).<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When travelling on Yorks Peninsula<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Yorke Peninsula, SA.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>6 years ago I found this plant growing in scrub lands near Point Turton. (at the bottom of the Peninsula) The peculiarity of its appearance was that it never came up,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>or was known, till<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the farmers rolled down the scrub mallee, &amp; ti-tree<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and burnt it. Directly the scrub was burnt: up came this plant and reached a height of from 7 to 8 feet, in some instances — It presented a handsome appearance, — the branches growing out from each side in a very symetrical manner, — looking very much like a candelabra.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I found the enclosed specimen on limestone country on Kangaroo Island,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>SA.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the "habitat" being exactly similar to that on southern Yorks Peninsula.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">W. Gill</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>30/3./1</p>
         </div>
